<DOC><DOCNO> AP880709-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0034EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-US     07-09 0150</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Thailand-US,0153</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. To Help Thai Border Villages</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States agreed Saturday toprovide an additional $5 million to aid Thai villagers living alongthe embattled borders with Laos and Cambodia, the U.S. Embassy said.   The agreement was initialed in a ceremony by visiting U.S.Secretary of State George P. Shultz and his Thai counterpart SiddhiSavetsila.   The funds, to be used to help some 300,000 Thais in 412villages, bring to $42 million the total amount Washington hasprovided since 1980 to help the frontier villagers, the embassysaid.   The funds are to be used to construct reservoirs and irrigationsystems, rural access roads and public health facilities in theborder area.   Fighting between Vietnamese and Cambodian guerrilla forcesfrequently spills into Thailand and border clashes between theThais and Laotians have flared periodically since communist forcestriumphed in that country in 1975.</TEXT></DOC>